79
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:06,703
But Ernie, do you want to give us kind of the short version of the follow-up and the details of the road and the problems with the insurance and so forth?

80
00:05:07,983 --> 00:05:08,864
Oh, OK.

81
00:05:08,984 --> 00:05:14,445
Well, was everyone able to read my email to the group earlier today?

82
00:05:15,255 --> 00:05:22,357
So we were, um, for the sake of this being a public meeting, you still need the executive summary.

83
00:05:22,677 --> 00:05:22,957
Yes.

84
00:05:23,017 --> 00:05:23,277
Yes.

85
00:05:23,457 --> 00:05:23,797
Okay.

86
00:05:24,417 --> 00:05:29,178
So I was in an automobile, uh, an accident with an automobile.

87
00:05:29,239 --> 00:05:41,882
I was on my bicycle, an accident with an automobile at the intersection of Smith lane and Wolverine streets in Medford on August 18th, where we.

88
00:05:43,595 --> 00:06:03,859
The driver of the automobile and I entered perpendicularly to each other and were involved in a collision wherein I was knocked unconscious and was sent to the ER Mass General Hospital for two days.

89
00:06:05,319 --> 00:06:09,040
In that happening, the driver of the automobile thought he had killed me.

90
00:06:09,120 --> 00:06:13,341
So he experienced a bit of trauma on his own psychologically.

91
00:06:15,211 --> 00:06:36,057
The important notices here are that I was traveling slightly downhill on Smith Lane, which is a narrow road, the right side of which was filled with huge potholes, forcing me to try to stay as close to the middle as possible.

92
00:06:36,978 --> 00:06:40,539
There was no signage at that intersection.

93
00:06:41,426 --> 00:07:09,167
The left side of the road had just been paved with fresh asphalt, continuing without interruption across Wilburn Street and onto the lane opposite, lending me visually with no other hints that perhaps I had the right of way, or certainly visually the stronger right of way when there is no other indication of who does.

94
00:07:10,804 --> 00:07:23,555
I was actually entering to cross Woburn Street from which on my left obscured by trees for both of us was an automobile coming at about 20 miles an hour.

95
00:07:24,435 --> 00:07:26,177
So I popped into his view.

96
00:07:26,437 --> 00:07:30,160
He swerved to the left to avoid hitting me directly.

97
00:07:30,781 --> 00:07:35,945
And I then crashed into his right rear door, bounced off the car.

98
00:07:36,883 --> 00:07:44,246
lots of road rash in the right side, was knocked unconscious, then spent two days at the ER.

99
00:07:46,727 --> 00:07:51,728
Up for discussion, I think, if we're getting to that point, are two important factors.

100
00:07:51,748 --> 00:07:53,469
One, oh, okay.

101
00:07:53,649 --> 00:07:57,471
So that was followed by a slow recovery.

102
00:07:57,511 --> 00:08:00,932
And then a couple of weeks ago, I visited the scene, spoke at length.

103
00:08:01,693 --> 00:08:19,149
with contiguous neighbors to the intersection, including the one who had rigged cam video, which was misinterpreted by the Medford police as to what actually happened, which is its own issue.

104
00:08:21,771 --> 00:08:28,577
They all agreed that some road calming needs to occur on Wolverine Street and that

105
00:08:28,946 --> 00:08:37,090
there are, as Daniel just mentioned, several such intersections where there's no markings at any of the four corners.

106
00:08:40,171 --> 00:08:56,639
It's interesting to note that while I was talking with these neighbors at length, I witnessed a teenage boy coming down the sidewalk on Smith Lane, perhaps trying to stay away from the potholes on the right side.

107
00:08:56,759 --> 00:08:57,920
So he was on the sidewalk,

108
00:08:58,633 --> 00:09:04,215
perhaps not knowing that there was a sheer cliff he was about to go over as there was no curb cut.

109
00:09:04,936 --> 00:09:22,563
So he bounced off the cliff, toppled over his handlebars and crashed right in front of us, which was just an incredible bit of deja vu for me, who did essentially the same kind of crash several weeks before.

110
00:09:24,332 --> 00:09:30,513
The neighbors agree that speed bumps or something are needed and that people race up and down Woburn Lane.

111
00:09:32,414 --> 00:09:35,735
So we need to get the potholes fixed for one.

112
00:09:36,195 --> 00:09:51,558
And secondly, if we get even one sign put up at that intersection, it should be on that slight downward slope of Smith Lane as it comes to Woburn and should be listed as a full stop.

113
00:09:52,460 --> 00:10:05,046
I don't know what to suggest as traffic calming measures on Wolburn Street or road, whatever it is, itself, as that's a much bigger topic.

114
00:10:05,266 --> 00:10:14,690
And, you know, Daniel, as an example, lives there and may have a whole, as well as all other neighbors will have a lot to say about what the needs are for Wolburn Street.

115
00:10:16,818 --> 00:10:39,875
that there was no publicity of this event, despite the fact that I was told by these witnesses that four to five cruisers showed up, a fire truck, and finally an EMT to cart me away is indicative of the fact that we don't have sufficient press for these kinds of activities occurring here.

116
00:10:40,493 --> 00:10:52,180
I happen to mention that to Daniel Kelly, Kennedy, my neighbor, who, you know, has been in journalism in this these parts for 40 years and was yelling about how yeah, we don't have a Medford newspaper anymore.

117
00:10:52,800 --> 00:10:54,601
So nobody finds out about this stuff.

118
00:10:55,181 --> 00:10:56,382
Unless you die, Ernie.

119
00:10:57,383 --> 00:10:59,664
Yeah, so I didn't make the channel five news.

120
00:11:02,682 --> 00:11:05,824
But I don't want this to get lost historically.

121
00:11:06,284 --> 00:11:16,910
In addition to taking on the charge of distributing bike lights to the kids, we'll talk about maybe helmets later.

122
00:11:16,930 --> 00:11:26,576
I'm obviously the obvious poster child to visit the schools and give out lights and talk about the need for kids to wear helmets.

123
00:11:27,293 --> 00:11:35,676
as all the principals and vice principals I've spoken with last spring and recently say it's a serious problem.

124
00:11:35,716 --> 00:11:45,779
The kids who do ride to school, you would think would be wearing helmets, but even those who ride back and forth to school do not.

125
00:11:47,279 --> 00:11:51,680
And school leadership is sort of at their wits as to how to deal with that.

126
00:11:55,068 --> 00:11:59,330
I guess I'll talk about the bike lights issues later in the agenda.

127
00:12:00,991 --> 00:12:04,853
I'm not sure what else to say about the accident.

128
00:12:05,354 --> 00:12:14,359
I did suffer subdural hematoma between the left and right hemispheres of my brain, fairly significant.

129
00:12:14,439 --> 00:12:20,062
It worsened over the first day and then subsided, at which point they kicked me out of there.

130
00:12:21,107 --> 00:12:27,032
just as my wife and I contracted COVID in the ER, because that's what happens when you go to an ER, you get COVID.

131
00:12:28,513 --> 00:12:45,747
So I'm clear of that and had a follow-up scan a week, eight days ago, which was red Thursday, stating that I'm progressing quite nicely, but that confusion, repetitiveness, memory loss, and

132
00:12:47,265 --> 00:12:55,075
imbalance issues will take a little more time to dissipate.

133
00:12:59,697 --> 00:13:03,799
I'll answer questions, of course, but I'm not sure what to add at this time.

134
00:13:04,459 --> 00:13:07,400
I think that's mostly what we need to know.

135
00:13:07,420 --> 00:13:25,448
A couple comments about what you had said earlier, though, just for the record, is one, Ernie, you mentioned that the insurance company was claiming that you ran a stop sign when, in fact, there is no stop sign at

136
00:13:26,708 --> 00:13:28,350
in any direction at that intersection.

137
00:13:28,370 --> 00:13:32,833
And also that you... Let me address that.

138
00:13:32,893 --> 00:13:48,806
The follow-up to that was that I indeed called them to have a kind of, you know, a conversation with someone in Texas at USAA and told them there was no stop sign there, that their assessor was being awfully creative.

139
00:13:49,890 --> 00:13:55,675
and they had testimony from me and said that they would reassess the situation at a higher level.

140
00:13:56,295 --> 00:14:14,450
I then got a letter from them yesterday stating that they no longer wanted from me $2,500 to fix the door of the car, but at the same time, they don't want to entertain a lawsuit from me for medical damages because I caused the accident by flying into the

141
00:14:15,677 --> 00:14:17,978
their insurance car.

142
00:14:18,598 --> 00:14:21,119
So they're talking out of two sides of their mouth there.

143
00:14:21,739 --> 00:14:30,982
But but they've lessened their they're not demanding money, but they're and they're also not talking about the stop sign.

144
00:14:31,503 --> 00:14:34,504
Somebody must have finally told them that there is no stop sign there.

145
00:14:35,044 --> 00:14:36,925
So your next point, Emily.

146
00:14:36,945 --> 00:14:38,005
Thanks.

147
00:14:40,375 --> 00:14:49,762
And then the other thing is that you had also mentioned that you didn't think that the police report gave an accurate description of what happened.

148
00:14:50,983 --> 00:14:51,203
No.

149
00:14:52,204 --> 00:14:59,950
He states that I caused the collision by ramming into the side of the car and that that was supported by the rig cam video.

150
00:15:00,330 --> 00:15:10,098
The drawing by the police shows the intersection not well mapped out and makes it look like a pure T-bone with me hitting

151
00:15:10,666 --> 00:15:10,886
them.

152
00:15:11,466 --> 00:15:13,047
It just wasn't carefully done.

153
00:15:13,467 --> 00:15:15,347
But I've been told that that's routine.

154
00:15:16,548 --> 00:15:22,409
And that fault assessment is often routinely an error.

155
00:15:22,829 --> 00:15:29,191
Also, at the at the attending officers initial report level.

156
00:15:30,571 --> 00:15:36,393
So I was told it is no surprise that the cops got it wrong in writing the initial report.

157
00:15:38,088 --> 00:15:49,113
So the fact that the woman who has the ring cam video responded to me when I asked to perhaps see it, said, you're not going to learn anything because it doesn't show the accident.

158
00:15:49,133 --> 00:15:51,554
It just shows you going down the hill by our house.

159
00:15:52,315 --> 00:15:55,816
Then you're obscured by the trees, as is the whole accident.

160
00:15:57,297 --> 00:16:02,960
Large bushes slash trees on that corner made it impossible for any of us to see each other.

161
00:16:04,921 --> 00:16:05,941
Bruce has his hand up.

162
00:16:10,113 --> 00:16:11,554
Hi there, thank you for recognizing me.

163
00:16:11,574 --> 00:16:14,957
There's just a few points that I wanted to make here.

164
00:16:15,898 --> 00:16:30,249
Some of them quoting from both the summary of the mass general law on the mass website, as well as I believe it's from the driver's handbook that is issued to people looking to get a motor vehicle license.

165
00:16:31,770 --> 00:16:33,332
And also some questions about

166
00:16:34,506 --> 00:16:50,937
uh, prejudices that, um, police may have against bicyclists in incidents like this, which anecdotally seems to occur from time to time with, um, officers who are less, just less familiar with bicycle operation.

167
00:16:51,478 --> 00:16:55,881
I know there's plenty of officers who are both in Medford and other communities.

168
00:16:56,641 --> 00:16:57,442
Um, but.

169
00:16:58,458 --> 00:17:13,806
There's enough of a pattern here that I think it bears maybe a discussion with the chief or whatever they do for training to make sure that there's not an implicit assumption that the cyclist is at fault.

170
00:17:14,667 --> 00:17:20,910
And unfortunately, I've got to say that many times that assumption comes from behavior of many cyclists.

171
00:17:21,627 --> 00:17:29,373
perhaps including ourselves, who are reluctant to adhere to the rules of the road for whatever reason.

172
00:17:29,573 --> 00:17:30,574
So I'll leave it at that.

173
00:17:31,194 --> 00:17:50,548
But regarding unsignalized intersections, Massachusetts is a bit of an anomaly, I believe, because in most cases, especially those states that subscribe to the Uniform Motor Vehicle Code, I forget the exact name of it,

174
00:17:52,308 --> 00:18:01,035
The code basically says that when you're entering a more major street from a minor street, that's the traffic that is supposed to yield.

175
00:18:02,275 --> 00:18:17,547
Massachusetts, however, does not subscribe to that code and specifically has a competing method of determining right-of-way, which is, from a practical standpoint, very unsafe.

176
00:18:18,467 --> 00:18:21,350
From a legal standpoint, might give you actually more

177
00:18:24,226 --> 00:18:29,049
perhaps more, I don't know what the word is, more rights, if you would.

178
00:18:29,370 --> 00:18:38,476
Now, I'm not a lawyer, I'm just reading what I'm reading here from the book, but it basically says, intersections not controlled by signs or signals.

179
00:18:39,556 --> 00:18:44,219
Slow down at an uncontrolled intersection, look left and right for oncoming traffic and proceed if the way is clear.

180
00:18:44,300 --> 00:18:44,600
However,

181
00:18:45,613 --> 00:18:54,356
You must yield the right-of-way to any vehicle that has entered the intersection from your right or is coming from your right.

182
00:18:54,996 --> 00:18:56,616
That would be you, Ernie, in this situation.

183
00:18:58,017 --> 00:18:59,577
Look for traffic coming from the left.

184
00:18:59,737 --> 00:19:05,419
Even though you may have a legal right-of-way, make sure that the other driver is yielding before you proceed.

185
00:19:06,520 --> 00:19:07,960
Now, that's what it says legally.

186
00:19:08,720 --> 00:19:14,002
Practically speaking, I believe that most people strongly interpret

187
00:19:14,945 --> 00:19:22,251
the major road having the right-of-way, and in particular, Woburn Street with a yellow line down the middle, and many other streets for that matter.

188
00:19:22,851 --> 00:19:28,216
I haven't looked at Grove Street, but I know we have a lot of side streets coming in.

189
00:19:29,256 --> 00:19:40,646
They are private ways, but there's no distinction made in the right-of-way rules listed here regarding private ways, although it's possible that there is a,

190
00:19:42,518 --> 00:19:49,500
something to do with driveways or other private ways in that regard, that maybe there's an interpretation there as well.

191
00:19:49,560 --> 00:19:51,821
Either way, it's quite ambiguous.

192
00:19:52,741 --> 00:20:00,263
And equally so with the pavement markings that you said that led you to believe that you had the right of way coming into there.

193
00:20:00,743 --> 00:20:05,965
And therefore, it didn't quite occur to you that you would need to observe traffic crossing.

194
00:20:06,225 --> 00:20:06,665
Yes, Ernie.

195
00:20:07,494 --> 00:20:28,515
Well, my reading, just from a simple Google search, confirmed my long-time belief, and I was trained in France, that even a small driveway, for instance, has right of way over a multi-lane, stronger highway coming across it.

196
00:20:29,447 --> 00:20:40,655
and then learn to reinforce with the advent of four-way stops in lots of neighborhoods, where we're all supposed to stop and yield to the person on the right and go around clockwise.

197
00:20:41,736 --> 00:20:45,178
That's along that same interpretation of the law.

198
00:20:45,698 --> 00:20:47,560
So I threw this at USAA.

199
00:20:48,160 --> 00:20:50,001
I said, look, there's no stop sign there.

200
00:20:50,562 --> 00:20:57,647
I actually had the right of way, as preposterous as it might seem, because Woburn is considered the more major road.

201
00:20:58,227 --> 00:21:04,950
The view at that intersection does not show Wolburn as the more major road as there's no yellow marking.

202
00:21:05,371 --> 00:21:18,838
And indeed, the new pavement is continuous through Smith Lane and not Wolburn, giving someone visually the impression that he or she is on the major road crossing.

203
00:21:18,878 --> 00:21:22,760
Well, I'll repeat the Massachusetts law makes no distinction

204
00:21:24,060 --> 00:21:26,662
about whether it's a major road or not.

205
00:21:27,182 --> 00:21:42,153
It just has to do with intersecting ways and I'll simply quote the, the chapter in verse here, literally, Mass General Law, chapter 89 section eight entitled right of way and intersecting ways.

206
00:21:42,813 --> 00:21:43,873
turning on red signals.

207
00:21:44,133 --> 00:21:49,575
And the first paragraph basically discusses several different types of intersections.

208
00:21:50,235 --> 00:22:00,717
But in particular, it makes mention of when two vehicles approach or enter an intersection of any ways as defined in section one of chapter 90.

209
00:22:00,777 --> 00:22:04,898
Now, I haven't referenced that, so I'd have to see if that includes private ways.

210
00:22:05,678 --> 00:22:12,240
At approximately the same instance, the operator of a vehicle on the left should yield the right of way to the vehicle on the right.

