: yeah I support copy the city council and then also talking about this specific example, though, of course, the letter will be general, but they do really appreciate specific example of something that has happened at some you know sort of as evidence.

406
00:43:35,415 --> 00:43:46,549
I wonder if copying the DPW might just save a few days in getting instructions to them to get those particular potholes filled more quickly.

407
00:43:47,714 --> 00:43:57,199
So if we're talking about the broader situation that's not as specific about those potholes, so I would write to them directly.

408
00:43:58,460 --> 00:44:03,343
You have their contact information, or I can if you don't want to, or somebody else can.

409
00:44:03,943 --> 00:44:10,127
But that's just as a one person write to them and say, this is a factor in this one particular spot.

410
00:44:12,588 --> 00:44:21,894
If we're writing a letter about the broader picture, I don't want to get too bogged down in the details of things that only affect this one spot.

411
00:44:21,914 --> 00:44:21,954
OK.

412
00:44:25,496 --> 00:44:28,798
So if that goes on CClickFix, that would be another thing to mention.

413
00:44:33,787 --> 00:44:39,470
But yeah, I think it would be great to copy the city council.

414
00:44:40,110 --> 00:44:52,795
And regarding ordinances, aside from the issue of having a patchwork of different traffic regulations in different cities,

415
00:44:53,878 --> 00:45:02,447
That still doesn't help actually tell people who has the right of way if the people who are at that intersection don't actually know what that ordinance says.

416
00:45:03,268 --> 00:45:14,701
So that also seems like an ordinance kind of clarifies things for the insurance companies after the fact, but most people don't.

417
00:45:15,923 --> 00:45:17,024
pay that much attention.

418
00:45:17,184 --> 00:45:24,688
And if there was a specific city ordinance that said, if there are no stop signs at this intersection, then here's what's supposed to happen.

419
00:45:24,728 --> 00:45:26,149
Most people would have no idea anyway.

420
00:45:26,169 --> 00:45:28,390
Right.

421
00:45:28,731 --> 00:45:34,594
So it wouldn't really change whether anybody actually crashed or not.

422
00:45:37,836 --> 00:45:41,298
So do we have a motion to send that letter?

423
00:45:41,318 --> 00:45:44,620
So moved.

424
00:45:47,907 --> 00:45:48,428
Seconded.

425
00:45:51,010 --> 00:45:51,610
All in favor.

426
00:45:51,630 --> 00:45:53,552
Yes.

427
00:45:54,673 --> 00:45:55,093
Opposed.

428
00:45:57,515 --> 00:46:01,539
Okay, I will write that letter and get it off as quick as I can.

429
00:46:08,502 --> 00:46:17,690
as maybe a request for a point of information in response to the point of information that you put up, Bruce, where you mentioned that Smith Lane is a private way.

430
00:46:18,470 --> 00:46:27,157
Maintenance is the responsibility of the owners there, but I assume that signalization is something that falls within the city's purview, right?

431
00:46:27,998 --> 00:46:29,599
That is a great question.

432
00:46:31,885 --> 00:46:41,589
I have no idea whether that is typically the case or whether the private way would be responsible for a sign facing there.

433
00:46:42,990 --> 00:46:55,836
Maybe that's part of why in Massachusetts, there's this weird dichotomy of all this stuff because private ways are much more common here than in many other states.

434
00:46:57,196 --> 00:47:00,278
Yeah, I was just assuming that maybe there's some,

435
00:47:01,614 --> 00:47:09,479
odd split in responsibilities where perhaps the city still pays for stop signs, but the residents might have to approve it's being put there.

436
00:47:09,780 --> 00:47:10,380
I don't know.

437
00:47:10,440 --> 00:47:15,844
Maybe so, or I do believe that there are private ways that

438
00:47:16,786 --> 00:47:30,894
perhaps the contract with the city or maybe because there are major, I don't know the details, but in some cases there may be snow removal, for example, as a possibility.

439
00:47:31,774 --> 00:47:36,237
On the other hand, I know several private ways around our area are plowed by private companies.

440
00:47:37,017 --> 00:47:41,900
So perhaps it's an agreement with a residence or a contract or something.

441
00:47:42,500 --> 00:47:45,642
I don't know the details on that as I don't live on a private way myself.

442
00:47:45,962 --> 00:47:50,823
I live on a private way and I get snow removal from the city.

443
00:47:51,443 --> 00:47:52,463
You do or you do not?

444
00:47:53,804 --> 00:47:55,744
I do get snow removal from the city.

445
00:47:55,764 --> 00:47:59,425
I did not even know that I was supposed to maintain my own road.

446
00:48:02,445 --> 00:48:12,347
From another vantage point, it would be clear that the city would want to protect Woburn Street by forcing private ways coming into it to have stop signs.

447
00:48:13,588 --> 00:48:15,008
So you can throw it on the city's

448
00:48:16,330 --> 00:48:17,911
or the state's back that way.

449
00:48:18,152 --> 00:48:33,525
Well, that's another, I think at this point we have, yeah, we'll see what we can do or we can see what comes of any letters that we send.

450
00:48:34,581 --> 00:48:52,948
It seems to me that if it turned out that, for whatever reason, the city couldn't put a stop sign on the private ways that intersect Woburn Street, they could still put stop signs on Woburn Street, which is maybe not preferable since that's the larger throughway, but it would still be safer than not having any stop signs at all.

451
00:48:52,968 --> 00:48:57,490
Or at least the signs showing that there's an intersection, a cross sign.

452
00:48:58,156 --> 00:49:06,344
So, and that, and again, if we're looking at things that might be applicable to other places as well, I think we should go on.

453
00:49:08,206 --> 00:49:13,250
We have, let's see, we mentioned the upcoming events.

454
00:49:15,232 --> 00:49:20,717
Vision Zero for Medford was the next item on the agenda.

455
00:49:20,757 --> 00:49:21,178
And I think

456
00:49:23,557 --> 00:49:31,800
Ellery sent something out about that very recently, or maybe, Gaston, you saw what was going on with that.

457
00:49:31,840 --> 00:49:33,660
I had a bit of a mad scramble today.

458
00:49:33,680 --> 00:49:38,682
So I didn't get myself up to speed.

459
00:49:40,162 --> 00:49:40,603
Gaston?

460
00:49:41,743 --> 00:49:43,283
Yeah, I think there was a nice discussion.

461
00:49:43,544 --> 00:49:45,344
Jared also commented.

462
00:49:45,364 --> 00:49:47,685
So I don't know whether you, Jared, want to go first.

463
00:49:48,367 --> 00:49:48,767
Sure.

464
00:49:49,288 --> 00:49:54,411
Well, I mean, I guess there's the Vision Zero and then Complete Streets, which are kind of tied together.

465
00:49:54,431 --> 00:49:55,352
Yeah, I responded.

466
00:49:55,392 --> 00:49:57,473
We can talk about Complete Streets later, because I just responded.

467
00:49:57,493 --> 00:49:58,834
I think there's some misunderstanding.

468
00:49:58,854 --> 00:50:00,155
So let's talk about Vision Zero.

469
00:50:00,175 --> 00:50:00,995
You can go ahead.

470
00:50:01,055 --> 00:50:01,236
Yeah.

471
00:50:01,436 --> 00:50:01,916
Sounds good.

472
00:50:01,936 --> 00:50:03,157
Well, I guess the...

473
00:50:04,611 --> 00:50:16,054
Vision Zero, I'm not sure exactly kind of, I guess that's something that a lot of municipal, I don't know a lot, but some fairly progressive municipalities have adopted kind of a Vision Zero policy.

474
00:50:17,615 --> 00:50:28,298
Whether or not that's something that happens through legislative ordinance or specifically by executive action, I'm not really sure how that's implemented.

475
00:50:28,318 --> 00:50:32,579
I'm not sure if it's consistently done across different municipalities.

476
00:50:32,639 --> 00:50:34,260
Maybe you can do it one way or the other.

477
00:50:35,084 --> 00:51:02,112
or maybe there's a wisdom to doing it one way or the other, but that's kind of a, I think it's a nonprofit organization that kind of set it up in the first place where it's really kind of a set of rules and priorities that cities can adopt where you're basically saying, you know, any amount of death on the roads, whether it's pedestrian or in a car or on a bike or whatever is unacceptable.

478
00:51:03,359 --> 00:51:14,404
Peter, you're a traffic engineer, so I'm sure maybe you know the details of this far better than I do, but it's generally setting up this framework of we do not accept death on the roads as an acceptable.

479
00:51:16,245 --> 00:51:17,286
Cost of doing business.

480
00:51:17,906 --> 00:51:18,226
What's that?

481
00:51:18,727 --> 00:51:20,427
An acceptable cost of doing business.

482
00:51:20,647 --> 00:51:21,348
Exactly, yeah.

483
00:51:21,428 --> 00:51:29,892
Yeah, I mean, in my understanding of the term as it's used, it is more of an aspirational thing than, I mean,

484
00:51:31,318 --> 00:51:37,326
Plenty of municipalities are Vision Zero cities that still have fatal crashes.

485
00:51:37,907 --> 00:51:38,228
Of course.

486
00:51:38,768 --> 00:51:44,897
It's just to say that the official position of the city is that we don't accept this and we're working

487
00:51:45,881 --> 00:51:48,683
we're working to stop this.

488
00:51:51,566 --> 00:52:00,753
Vision Zero, in my mind, there may be some differing opinion among activist groups.

489
00:52:01,573 --> 00:52:06,577
To my mind, Vision Zero is an aspiration, but there's not much in the way of teeth.

490
00:52:06,678 --> 00:52:07,838
There's no teeth to Vision Zero.

491
00:52:07,858 --> 00:52:09,220
You can call yourself Vision Zero City.

492
00:52:10,675 --> 00:52:11,656
fatalities can go up.

493
00:52:11,757 --> 00:52:14,261
And if you haven't worked on it, that's your problem.

494
00:52:14,342 --> 00:52:16,626
And you still technically call yourself a vision zero city.

495
00:52:17,818 --> 00:52:18,799
It's all words.

496
00:52:19,900 --> 00:52:20,120
Sure.

497
00:52:20,720 --> 00:52:20,941
Yeah.

498
00:52:21,041 --> 00:52:29,047
I mean, I guess it's something that, you know, it is like aspirational, it's a philosophy, it's a goal.

499
00:52:29,067 --> 00:52:40,657
I suppose it's something that I would still like it to be the goal of the city, you know, whether, you know, obviously you can't remove like all death from the roads.

500
00:52:41,433 --> 00:52:45,076
The question is, is it something that you're actively trying to prevent?

501
00:52:45,416 --> 00:52:48,919
Are you putting efforts towards stopping it?

502
00:52:49,139 --> 00:52:51,341
That's what in practice it's supposed to be.

503
00:52:51,361 --> 00:53:09,375
I know that there has been in some corners of the active transportation, sustainable transportation world, some cynicism about that because you have major cities calling themselves vision zero cities and doing not much.

504
00:53:13,177 --> 00:53:33,106
So my question about this in terms of what this could potentially actually mean on the ground in Medford is, it seems to me that adopting this as a policy or as an aspiration, as a goal,

505
00:53:34,876 --> 00:53:53,849
When that comes, the way that that would manifest in a concrete way is, for example, we've talked about Medford Square being a wretched intersection to get through on foot or on bike, and it's not that much fun in a car, and that when they talk about how to redesign Medford Square,

506
00:53:54,610 --> 00:53:59,094
They say, well, you can't change the pattern because then you would have lower traffic flow.

507
00:53:59,754 --> 00:54:05,238
And all of the alternatives would allow for lower volume.

508
00:54:05,739 --> 00:54:11,383
Therefore, we have to keep it the way that it is, even though it's more dangerous for everybody else.

509
00:54:11,704 --> 00:54:17,288
And the Vision Zero aspiration would be to say, well, we're going to change our priorities.

510
00:54:17,548 --> 00:54:21,371
So we're willing to accept lower through flow

511
00:54:22,572 --> 00:54:28,396
for the sake of making it safer and more user-friendly for everyone else.

512
00:54:29,096 --> 00:54:31,518
And that would be certainly the hope.

513
00:54:33,919 --> 00:54:38,022
And so my question is, if we convince

514
00:54:39,106 --> 00:54:41,527
Medford to adopt this as their goal.

515
00:54:42,367 --> 00:54:46,428
Are we actually going to get that reshuffling of priorities out of it?

516
00:54:47,129 --> 00:55:08,696
And do we, and how do we make it clear that this is the, um, that this is what we're ultimately going to be asking for at some point, there will come a point where we're asking to slow down vehicular traffic or, um, reduce the number of cars that can get through a certain intersection and a certain amount of time in order to make it.

517
00:55:09,356 --> 00:55:10,437
safer for everybody else.

518
00:55:13,319 --> 00:55:20,724
So that's, I don't know what that means for us asking Medford to adopt this.

519
00:55:22,125 --> 00:55:24,206
That's what I hope that we would get out of it.

520
00:55:24,626 --> 00:55:26,327
Yeah, that's what I think it should be.

521
00:55:26,467 --> 00:55:37,635
I think it should be about priorities and about whether you want the most number of cars in the lowest amount of time, or if you want the safest possible experience for all users.

522
00:55:40,086 --> 00:55:40,486
Gaston?

523
00:55:41,667 --> 00:55:44,008
Yes, I completely agree with everything that has been said.

524
00:55:45,269 --> 00:55:52,373
So I just want to add that, so Boston, Cambridge, and Somerville are Vision Zero communities.

525
00:55:52,873 --> 00:56:08,081
So I also add that if we can convince the administration to jump on board, I think it should also serve as a motivator to sort of work together

526
00:56:08,830 --> 00:56:20,500
with Somerville in particular, because it's neighbor to us and sort of, you know, work more at the metro level to, you know, link all the places together.

527
00:56:20,620 --> 00:56:27,887
Because, you know, I feel like a lot of people are, you know, they don't just bike within Medford, but they might be going somewhere else.

528
00:56:27,907 --> 00:56:31,070
So I think if we can convince the administration

529
00:56:32,132 --> 00:56:34,373
you know, sign up to be a Vision Zero community.

530
00:56:34,413 --> 00:56:35,614
Of course, it's an aspirational thing.

531
00:56:35,654 --> 00:56:42,117
And then we'll talk later about the working group on how, you know, we can help that happen, implement that.

532
00:56:42,177 --> 00:56:48,439
But at the same time, I think, you know, we're just working together with our neighbors, basically.

533
00:56:48,579 --> 00:56:49,600
And I think that's important.

534
00:56:50,740 --> 00:56:51,061
Becca?

535
00:56:53,162 --> 00:56:59,544
Yeah, I'm not a big expert on Vision Zero, but one of the things is my understanding that

536
00:57:01,143 --> 00:57:02,064
HAB-Juliette Boone, COB.:

537
00:57:02,064 --> 00:57:11,151
: You know, ideal for if a city were to adopt that is that when there are crashes that there is an invest sort of a more investigation and.

538
00:57:12,108 --> 00:57:17,312
kind of study done so that there's a process that's built in.

539
00:57:17,892 --> 00:57:23,717
So the circumstances of the crashes, there's a way to kind of remedy them.

540
00:57:23,797 --> 00:57:29,281
So it's not just things go off the radar, it's kind of recorded more formally.

541
00:57:29,341 --> 00:57:34,265
There's more kind of awareness of the police and how they do that.

542
00:57:34,965 --> 00:57:43,549
and then there's kind of a follow-up, like there's a crash at an intersection, what can we do to evaluate to see if we can improve this situation?

543
00:57:43,569 --> 00:58:00,717
So it's kind of built in, in certain sort of like city operations, but I'm curious how other kind of neighboring cities do that, because I, you know, there is some of that, but I know that, you know, it's not necessarily held to it, but it's like what, maybe it's what Medford wants to kind of

544
00:58:01,282 --> 00:58:07,927
you know, practical steps built in, not just necessarily aspirational, but what practical steps could be incorporated.

545
00:58:07,947 --> 00:58:11,450
Yeah, I think that's a great point.

546
00:58:11,510 --> 00:58:24,099
And especially given what we were just talking about with, um, with Ernie's accident and the other intersections that look a lot like that, and presumably have a lot of the same potential problems.

547
00:58:24,980 --> 00:58:25,260
Jared.

548
00:58:26,550 --> 00:58:29,212
Yeah, I mean, I totally agree with what with what Becca said.

549
00:58:29,232 --> 00:58:38,700
They're seeing an actual outcome after any type of event like that just seems to be like a demonstration that you are trying to do something about it.

550
00:58:39,521 --> 00:58:50,010
I feel like, you know, maybe it's a, maybe this is too slow progress, but in Somerville, like one of the critiques that people sometimes make is that they're a vision zero place and basically

551
00:58:51,194 --> 00:58:54,976
someone dies on a bike and then they build a bike lane, right?

552
00:58:55,016 --> 00:58:57,337
Like that's, it's kind of this like one for one thing.

553
00:58:57,397 --> 00:58:59,638
Someone gets doored, someone dies on a bike.

554
00:58:59,658 --> 00:59:05,681
It's like, all right, well, I guess that's enough like pressure on us to then do something substantial.

555
00:59:05,741 --> 00:59:13,685
That's a very like kind of dark way to think about it that it takes a death to like get a bike lane, a very like dark and transactional approach.

556
00:59:14,506 --> 00:59:16,627
But there is something to be said for,

557
00:59:17,935 --> 00:59:23,040
a thing happens that you do not want and you respond with some type of improvement.

558
00:59:23,080 --> 00:59:39,155
It doesn't have to be quite so waiting for a death, I think, but not just letting things like what happened with Ernie go or any number of things that happen like that that we don't know about, or a kid getting hit on Summer Street a while back and ending up in a full body cast.

559
00:59:39,736 --> 00:59:43,219
These are things that do require remediation.

560
00:59:45,755 --> 00:59:47,017
Yeah, I think you're right.

561
00:59:47,097 --> 00:59:56,408
And I think having a process for assessing what happened when there is a crash.

562
00:59:57,711 --> 01:00:01,592
And how can this be improved?

563
01:00:01,812 --> 01:00:07,553
And how could those improvements be carried across other places that look like that across the rest of the city?

564
01:00:07,573 --> 01:00:10,074
I think that is really important.

565
01:00:10,114 --> 01:00:20,596
And a lot of the time when crashes do happen, especially if it's a relatively minor one, it's barely recorded at all.

566
01:00:21,916 --> 01:00:24,797
And there's not a lot of analysis done

567
01:00:25,812 --> 01:00:38,239
And, you know, and I think the minor crashes actually could be potentially really useful information too, because a lot of the same things that cause major crashes also sometimes cause minor crashes.

568
01:00:38,840 --> 01:00:46,844
And if you can get the same useful information from somebody who didn't die, that's better.

569
01:00:46,864 --> 01:00:52,528
I mean, that's like, going back to Jared's

570
01:00:53,475 --> 01:00:57,737
comment about it being a dark and transactional way of looking at things.

571
01:00:58,617 --> 01:01:06,161
Um, if it, if it takes somebody dying for the city of Somerville to decide, oh, well, I guess we really do need a bike lane there.

572
01:01:07,021 --> 01:01:14,004
Maybe they could have found that out if somebody survived, they still, um, the same thing could have happened for the same reason.

573
01:01:15,545 --> 01:01:15,985
Ernie, go ahead.

574
01:01:16,492 --> 01:01:23,177
You know, I agree with what Jared said, but I'll put a lighter cast on it and just say that it's firefighting.

575
01:01:23,738 --> 01:01:30,924
You know, what happened to me was a fire and you fight it and put it out quickly by, you know, treating that intersection, et cetera.

576
01:01:31,424 --> 01:01:32,425
It shouldn't disappear.

577
01:01:32,445 --> 01:01:42,073
And I'm taken again by your comments and saying that bicyclists are going to have to get creative with contra flows and taking minor routes

578
01:01:42,573 --> 01:01:44,954
in order to improve safety of flow through the city.

579
01:01:45,414 --> 01:01:54,337
And that really does beg what we're talking about in the general sense of establishing right of way of those secondary intersections.

580
01:01:54,898 --> 01:01:55,778
That's very important.

581
01:01:56,018 --> 01:01:58,179
I think that was important that you noted that.

582
01:02:01,200 --> 01:02:02,040
So what do we need?

583
01:02:02,660 --> 01:02:03,781
Jared has his hand up.

584
01:02:04,201 --> 01:02:09,283
Sorry, I just had a quick comment about the Vision Zero thing in general, just to kind of circle back to that.

585
01:02:11,005 --> 01:02:12,926
I recognize that it's an aspirational thing.

586
01:02:13,006 --> 01:02:26,017
I think the thing to recognize though, is that if we are to move forward with something like that, we are advisors to the city, but we're not the city in the same way that the city staff is.

587
01:02:26,077 --> 01:02:27,819
We don't control the money, right?

588
01:02:29,300 --> 01:02:33,584
So what I wanna be clear is that if we're able to move forward with something like this,

589
01:02:34,404 --> 01:02:43,689
It's really important that it become the city's aspiration and not simply our aspiration as a bike committee.

590
01:02:43,729 --> 01:02:47,891
People already know that we care about bikes and we want people to be biking and be safe biking.

591
01:02:48,491 --> 01:02:52,113
We need other people to be on board with that as well.

592
01:02:52,193 --> 01:02:56,115
The people who do control the policy and the finances of the city.

593
01:02:56,675 --> 01:02:59,256
So I think there, our power is

594
01:03:01,568 --> 01:03:06,212
to some extent limited to be power of persuasion more than power of directive.

595
01:03:07,053 --> 01:03:12,798
And it's probably worth taking that into account when we're figuring out how to move forward with something like this.

596
01:03:13,507 --> 01:03:29,152
So I think the thing that we can really ultimately do is make recommendations that Medford adopt a Vision Zero policy, but more than just say, well, we're the bike commission and we think Vision Zero is a good idea.

597
01:03:30,472 --> 01:03:39,475
Maybe our recommendation should also include here's what we think that means in terms of,

598
01:03:40,270 --> 01:03:46,324
changes that the city should adopt and and one of them might be.

599
01:03:48,933 --> 01:03:56,497
the change in prioritizing, for example, safety versus maximizing traffic flow.

600
01:03:57,938 --> 01:04:14,046
And then the other thing might be putting in a process for assessing the things that the city could do to mitigate the reasons behind crashes that happen and look for other places in the city that have similar circumstances and fix those too.

601
01:04:16,320 --> 01:04:19,682
And there may be other things that we would include on that list.

602
01:04:20,503 --> 01:04:36,354
So my question right now is, if we are going to move forward with recommending a Vision Zero policy, what kind of recommendations are we actually making, and also to whom?

603
01:04:42,820 --> 01:04:45,201
Does anybody have- It's a good question.

